events.description: Triumph of Orthodoxy: Empress Theodora II restores the veneration of icons in the Orthodox churches in the Byzantine Empire.
events.html: • 843 – Triumph of Orthodoxy: Empress Theodora II restores the veneration of icons in the Orthodox churches in the Byzantine Empire.[1]

events.description: Arnošt of Pardubice becomes the last Bishop of Prague (3 March 1343 O.S.), and, a year later, the first Archbishop of Prague.
events.html: • 1343 – Arnošt of Pardubice becomes the last Bishop of Prague (3 March 1343 O.S.), and, a year later, the first Archbishop of Prague.[2]

entities.name: List of bishops and archbishops of Prague

events.description: Battle of Castagnaro: Padua, led by John Hawkwood, is victorious over Giovanni Ordelaffi of Verona.
events.html: • 1387 – Battle of Castagnaro: Padua, led by John Hawkwood, is victorious over Giovanni Ordelaffi of Verona.[3]

events.description: Guaraní forces living in the Jesuit reductions defeat bandeirantes loyal to the Portuguese Empire at the Battle of Mbororé in present-day Panambí, Argentina.
events.html: • 1641 – Guaraní forces living in the Jesuit reductions defeat bandeirantes loyal to the Portuguese Empire at the Battle of Mbororé in present-day Panambí, Argentina.[4]

events.description: The Frondeurs and the French government sign the Peace of Rueil.
events.html: • 1649 – The Frondeurs and the French government sign the Peace of Rueil.[5]

events.description: The Daily Courant, England's first national daily newspaper, is published for the first time.
events.html: • 1702 – The Daily Courant, England's first national daily newspaper, is published for the first time.[6]

events.description: Queen Anne withholds Royal Assent from the Scottish Militia Bill, the last time a British monarch vetoes legislation.
events.html: • 1708 – Queen Anne withholds Royal Assent from the Scottish Militia Bill, the last time a British monarch vetoes legislation.[7]

events.description: The signing of the Treaty of Mangalore brings the Second Anglo-Mysore War to an end.
events.html: • 1784 – The signing of the Treaty of Mangalore brings the Second Anglo-Mysore War to an end.[8]

events.description: The Battle of Kharda is fought between the Maratha Confederacy and the Nizam of Hyderabad, resulting in Maratha victory.
events.html: • 1795 – The Battle of Kharda is fought between the Maratha Confederacy and the Nizam of Hyderabad, resulting in Maratha victory.[9]

events.description: Flagstaff War: Unhappy with translational differences regarding the Treaty of Waitangi, chiefs Hōne Heke, Kawiti and Māori tribe members chop down the British flagpole for a fourth time and drive settlers out of Kororāreka, New Zealand.
events.html: • 1845 – Flagstaff War: Unhappy with translational differences regarding the Treaty of Waitangi, chiefs Hōne Heke, Kawiti and Māori tribe members chop down the British flagpole for a fourth time and drive settlers out of Kororāreka, New Zealand.[10]

events.description: Louis-Hippolyte Lafontaine and Robert Baldwin become the first Prime Ministers of the Province of Canada to be democratically elected under a system of responsible government.
events.html: • 1848 – Louis-Hippolyte Lafontaine and Robert Baldwin become the first Prime Ministers of the Province of Canada to be democratically elected under a system of responsible government.[11]

events.description: The first performance of Rigoletto by Giuseppe Verdi takes place in Venice.
events.html: • 1851 – The first performance of Rigoletto by Giuseppe Verdi takes place in Venice.[12]

events.description: American Civil War: The Constitution of the Confederate States of America is adopted.
events.html: • 1861 – American Civil War: The Constitution of the Confederate States of America is adopted.[13]

events.description: The Great Sheffield Flood kills 238 people in Sheffield, England.
events.html: • 1864 – The Great Sheffield Flood kills 238 people in Sheffield, England.[14]

events.description: Construction of the Seven Sisters Colliery, South Wales, begins; it is located on one of the richest coal sources in Britain.
events.html: • 1872 – Construction of the Seven Sisters Colliery, South Wales, begins; it is located on one of the richest coal sources in Britain.[15]

events.description: Shō Tai formally abdicates his position of King of Ryūkyū, under orders from Tokyo, ending the Ryukyu Kingdom.
events.html: • 1879 – Shō Tai formally abdicates his position of King of Ryūkyū, under orders from Tokyo, ending the Ryukyu Kingdom.[16]

events.description: The Great Blizzard of 1888 begins along the eastern seaboard of the United States, shutting down commerce and killing more than 400 people.
events.html: • 1888 – The Great Blizzard of 1888 begins along the eastern seaboard of the United States, shutting down commerce and killing more than 400 people.[17]

events.description: World War I: Mesopotamian campaign: Baghdad falls to Anglo-Indian forces commanded by General Frederick Stanley Maude.
events.html: • 1917 – World War I: Mesopotamian campaign: Baghdad falls to Anglo-Indian forces commanded by General Frederick Stanley Maude.[18]

events.description: In New York City, Samuel Roxy Rothafel opens the Roxy Theatre.
events.html: • 1927 – In New York City, Samuel Roxy Rothafel opens the Roxy Theatre.[19]

events.description: World War II: United States President Franklin D. Roosevelt signs the Lend-Lease Act into law, allowing American-built war supplies to be shipped to the Allies on loan.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: United States President Franklin D. Roosevelt signs the Lend-Lease Act into law, allowing American-built war supplies to be shipped to the Allies on loan.[20]

events.description: World War II:  The Imperial Japanese Navy attempts a large-scale kamikaze attack on the U.S. Pacific Fleet anchored at Ulithi atoll in Operation Tan No. 2.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: The Imperial Japanese Navy attempts a large-scale kamikaze attack on the U.S. Pacific Fleet anchored at Ulithi atoll in Operation Tan No. 2.[21]

events.description: World War II: The Empire of Vietnam, a short-lived Japanese puppet state, is established.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: The Empire of Vietnam, a short-lived Japanese puppet state, is established.[22]

events.description: Rudolf Höss, the first commandant of Auschwitz concentration camp, is captured by British troops.
events.html: • 1946 – Rudolf Höss, the first commandant of Auschwitz concentration camp, is captured by British troops.[23]

events.description: The 1977 Hanafi Siege: Around 150 hostages held in Washington, D.C., by Hanafi Muslims are set free after ambassadors from three Islamic nations join negotiations.
events.html: • 1977 – The 1977 Hanafi Siege: Around 150 hostages held in Washington, D.C., by Hanafi Muslims are set free after ambassadors from three Islamic nations join negotiations.[24]

events.description: Coastal Road massacre: At least 37 are killed and more than 70 are wounded when Fatah hijack an Israeli bus, prompting Israel's Operation Litani.
events.html: • 1978 – Coastal Road massacre: At least 37 are killed and more than 70 are wounded when Fatah hijack an Israeli bus, prompting Israel's Operation Litani.[25]

events.description: Hundreds of students protest in the University of Pristina in Kosovo, then part of Yugoslavia, to give their province more political rights. The protests then became a nationwide movement.
events.html: • 1981 – Hundreds of students protest in the University of Pristina in Kosovo, then part of Yugoslavia, to give their province more political rights. The protests then became a nationwide movement.[26]

events.description: Fifteen people are killed when Widerøe Flight 933 crashes into the Barents Sea near Gamvik, Norway.
events.html: • 1982 – Fifteen people are killed when Widerøe Flight 933 crashes into the Barents Sea near Gamvik, Norway.[27]

events.description: Bob Hawke is appointed Prime Minister of Australia.
events.html: • 1983 – Bob Hawke is appointed Prime Minister of Australia.[28]

events.description: Mikhail Gorbachev is elected to the position of General Secretary of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union, making Gorbachev the USSR's de facto, and last, head of state.
events.html: • 1985 – Mikhail Gorbachev is elected to the position of General Secretary of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union, making Gorbachev the USSR's de facto, and last, head of state.[29]

events.description: Lithuania declares independence from the Soviet Union.
events.html: • 1990 – Lithuania declares independence from the Soviet Union.[30]

entities.name: Act of the Re-Establishment of the State of Lithuania

events.description: Patricio Aylwin is sworn in as the first democratically elected President of Chile since 1970.
events.html: • 1990 – Patricio Aylwin is sworn in as the first democratically elected President of Chile since 1970.[31]

events.description: The International Criminal Court holds its inaugural session in The Hague.
events.html: • 2003 – The International Criminal Court holds its inaugural session in The Hague.[32]

events.description: Madrid train bombings: Simultaneous explosions on rush hour trains in Madrid, Spain kill 191 people.
events.html: • 2004 – Madrid train bombings: Simultaneous explosions on rush hour trains in Madrid, Spain kill 191 people.[33]

events.description: Michelle Bachelet is inaugurated as the first female president of Chile.
events.html: • 2006 – Michelle Bachelet is inaugurated as the first female president of Chile.[34]

events.description: Winnenden school shooting: Fifteen are killed and nine are injured before recent graduate Tim Kretschmer shoots and kills himself, leading to tightened weapons restrictions in Germany.
events.html: • 2009 – Winnenden school shooting: Fifteen are killed and nine are injured before recent graduate Tim Kretschmer shoots and kills himself, leading to tightened weapons restrictions in Germany.[35]

events.description: Economist and businessman Sebastián Piñera is sworn in as President of Chile. Aftershocks of the 2010 Pichilemu earthquakes hit central Chile during the ceremony.
events.html: • 2010 – Economist and businessman Sebastián Piñera is sworn in as President of Chile. Aftershocks of the 2010 Pichilemu earthquakes hit central Chile during the ceremony.[36]

events.description: An earthquake measuring 9.0 in magnitude strikes 130 km (81 mi) east of Sendai, Japan, triggering a tsunami killing thousands of people. This event also triggered the second largest nuclear accident in history, and one of only two events to be classified as a Level 7 on the International Nuclear Event Scale.
events.html: • 2011 – An earthquake measuring 9.0 in magnitude strikes 130 km (81 mi) east of Sendai, Japan, triggering a tsunami killing thousands of people. This event also triggered the second largest nuclear accident in history, and one of only two events to be classified as a Level 7 on the International Nuclear Event Scale.[37]

events.description: A U.S. soldier kills 16 civilians in the Panjwayi District of Afghanistan near Kandahar.
events.html: • 2012 – A U.S. soldier kills 16 civilians in the Panjwayi District of Afghanistan near Kandahar.[38]

events.description: A Bombardier Challenger 604 crashes into the Zagros Mountains near the Iranian city of Shar-e-kord, killing all 11 people on board.
events.html: • 2018 – A Bombardier Challenger 604 crashes into the Zagros Mountains near the Iranian city of Shar-e-kord, killing all 11 people on board.[39]

events.description: The World Health Organization (WHO) declares the COVID-19 virus epidemic a pandemic.
events.html: • 2020 – The World Health Organization (WHO) declares the COVID-19 virus epidemic a pandemic.[40]

events.html: • 2021 – US President Joe Biden signs the $1.9 trillion American Rescue Plan into law.[41]
